\fs28 Parsing in Keyboard Maestro
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 Because the output is predictably separated by colons, you can easily extract these values in Keyboard Maestro using a 
\f0\b Search using Regular Expression
\f1\b0  action on the \cf3 \cb4 HTML Result Button\cf2 \cb1  variable.\
A standard regex pattern to split these into your local variables would look like this:\
\cf3 \cb4 ^([^:]*):([^:]*):([^:]*):(.*)$\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 \cb1 HTML Input String Return Specification
\fs28 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 Unlike the \cf3 \cb4 HTML Result Button\cf2 \cb1 \'97which returns a single parsed string of the event that closed the prompt\'97text entered into input fields is pushed 
\f0\b directly
\f1\b0  to Keyboard Maestro variables immediately before the prompt submits and closes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 Mapping Inputs to Keyboard Maestro Variables\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 The name of the Keyboard Maestro variable that gets populated is dictated entirely by the \cf3 \cb4 id\cf2 \cb1  you assign to the input in your JSON configuration.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 JSON Configuration Example:
\f1\b0\fs48 \cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 \cb7 \{\
  \cf8 "type"\cf3 : \cf9 "input"\cf3 ,\
  \cf8 "id"\cf3 : \cf9 \'93MyUserInput"\cf3 ,\
  \cf8 "default"\cf3 : \cf9 "Type here..."\cf3 \
\}
\fs28 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

